##### **§1. Phenomenon Overview**

Our chosen phenomenon focuses on the fabrication of echo chambers created from interactions between bots on X regarding discussions of current real-world disasters. We particularly highlight how bots manipulate users seeking information by spreading disinformation, leading users to believe the content they see as accurate. Hajli et al. (2022) speak about the formation of these echo chambers and opinion manipulation, stating “social bots spread a given on-line opinion over social media platforms, leading to the misconception that other humans share the ‘bot opinion’” (p. 1246). Through bots using techniques to prevent being detected and removed, such as interacting with one another to auto sort, disinformation AI bots ultimately end up also interacting with the AI recommendation algorithms on X. These bots then deceive the algorithms by using numerous techniques that make the platform’s algorithms believe that their content is popular. Tahora Hossein Nazer (2019) states that one of these techniques is that “These bots latch trending hashtags to their messages to push them higher in the social media search results” (p. 12). During disasters, these hashtags tend to relate to the present disaster event, and as such they have many more eyes on them than most other hashtags. As a result, posts containing misinformation made by the bots are spread throughout the media ecosystem to consumers by recommendation algorithms. This creates a snowball effect, as more users engage with the posts and drive analytics for the recommendation algorithms to push the bot-driven disinformation more alongside new posts made by causally misinformed humans. 

The issue is crucial as it concerns the reliability of information during situations where many people may be in a vulnerable state and are looking to these platforms for updates and informative news. Learning how these bad actors behave and how they spread their influence is instrumental to preventing the spread of disinformation from being as severe in future disasters, ensuring that reliable information in future situations doesn’t become warped or ignored. Through our research, we hope to emphasize the importance and need for platforms such as X to work on solutions to detect these bots and remove them for the well-being of their users.

Agent-based modelling offers a reliable approach to investigating the impact of these bots. While not entirely accurate, it supports modelling the effects of malicious bots and how to prevent their influence. Using agent-based modelling, we can conduct our research and testing without needing a disaster to occur in real-time, allowing us to be proactive in preventative measures of these bots before the platform abuse happens. Agent-based modelling enables us to conduct investigations and tests consistently and efficiently, without interference from real-world variables.

##### **§2. Simulation Design & Implementation**

The simulation occurs within a grid-based ecosystem, based on the Schelling Segregation model. In our model, agents can exist as either humans or bots. Unlike the Schelling Segregation model, each agent is given multiple types, and human agents are dynamic and can change their types. Each agent has a "class" type, which specifies whether they are human or a bot. The second type is “knowledge” which indicates disinformation or information. For human agents, it would represent those who are informed or misinformed. For bot agents, it would represent whether they are informational or producing disinformation. At the start of the simulation, agents are randomly placed around this grid, and all human agents are considered informed. Additionally, a small portion of agent bots are randomly placed and divided into opposite “knowledge” types. Similar to the default Schelling model, human agents will self-sort to be near other agents with a similar "knowledge" type. In this case, they are sufficiently “happy” when the majority of the agents surrounding them share their “knowledge” type, regardless of whether those agents are bots and can move if they are unhappy. This interaction creates echo chambers over time. Additionally, human agents might adjust their “knowledge” type if they are near a bot agent of opposite knowledge types as bot agents can influence their human agent neighbours, with a chance each step of making the human agent misinformed or informed. Bot agents will move only when a neighbouring human agent shares the same knowledge type, as its goal of influencing has been completed and they will seek out another human agent to convert. Bot agents will never be next to one another, to mimic auto sorting and prevention of being discovered by the platforms.

All agents will take an action each turn or “step”, which can be a variety of behaviours. This includes moving due to being unhappy, changing their “knowledge” type to become misinformed, or remaining in place since they are happy. Since we are using RandomActivation, steps happen consistently. Bot agents will attempt to remain in place as long as they are not near other bot agents or are “in the process” of influencing a human agent of the opposite knowledge type to be the same knowledge type. In this, two bot-to-bot interactions occur. The first interaction happens through the bot agents interacting with the simulation itself and represents how the bot agents will move when they are no longer able to influence the agents around them, representing the social platform’s algorithm pushing what the bots say further to more users on the platform since it generates engagement. The second bot-to-bot interaction is between the bot agents, as they will move away from each other if they find themselves neighbours since this helps them affect as many other human agents as possible. Through these bot-to-bot interactions, echo chambers emerge as we simulate bots spreading disinformation to human neighbours, relocating across the platform to expand their presence, and evading detection.

The data that we plan to collect is the overall happiness and the variance in the “knowledge” type of agents. The overall happiness data is defaulted to the Schelling Segregation model, however, it assists in representing the creation of echo chambers. Additionally, through the variance in the “knowledge” type, we can see how the radicalization of the platform changes over time

##### **§3. Preliminary Observations & Results**

The simulation displays how bots, during a time of disaster and when users are most vulnerable, will take advantage of humans and spread disinformation. Humans are often unsure whether a user is a bot and may be susceptible to the information being spread. Through the unknown of whether bot sources are trustworthy, they can influence the users of a platform to create echo chambers and radicalization. 

![][image9]

The chart above illustrates how bots contributed to the formation of disinformed human agents, ultimately lowering the number of total humans informed and leading to the creation of echo chambers. Based on the chart, bots can affect over a third of the human agents before their influence slows and human agents begin to self-sort so that fewer human agents are readily available for bots to disinform. Although human agents cannot identify bots, they can recognize agents with opposing opinions and will attempt to avoid them. This highlights the limitations of real-world disinformation bots and explains why disasters are critical opportunities for them to gain influence. During disasters these barriers are essentially removed, creating an environment on a platform similar to the start of this simulation.

Hills and valleys are also visible within the graph, displaying the attempts at re-informing human agents by informational bots. Because disinformation bots vastly outnumber them, they cannot reverse the effects. However, they help limit the influence of disinformation bots and can inform some individuals.

![][image10]

The above graph displays the number of clusters of like-minded human agents throughout the simulation, formed when human agents are happy with those around them and decide to remain in place. This is a prime example of the effect of bots on echo chambers, as all of these clusters are the results of disinformation from bots \- creating a situation where more and more disinformed users are avoiding informed users, and vice-versa. This also makes it harder for the informational bots to break the influence of the disinformation bots. Not only are the users they are trying to inform avoiding the informational bots (as they share the opposite opinion) but they are also clumped together, making it harder to “break in” to their echo chamber and have an effect.

##### ![][image11]

	The above graph shows an interesting and unexpected phenomenon that became apparent during testing \- the happiness of agents on the platform stayed relatively consistent at any given point during the test. Although this may seem unremarkable at first, it could indicate a deeper challenge in detecting bots on platforms and the formation of echo chambers. With the current implementation, this is based on a fraction of the number of neighbouring agents next to an agent who share the same beliefs, and whether this fraction is below the homophily.

The large drop shows the impacts of disinformation beginning to be spread, accurate to the real world when a disaster drastically occurs and bots activate and begin taking advantage of users to spread disinformation on platforms.

##### **§4. Challenges & Next Steps**

The original plan for the model involved having agents exist on a spectrum of types, where they could be radicalized in different directions (for example, a value of 0 would mean they are informed, whereas \-1 is disinformed in one way and 1 is disinformed in a completely separate way). During times without a “Disaster” active during the simulation, human agents would only change type due to other human agents influencing one another through information or disinformation. Bot agents would only be prevalent during the “disaster” times of the simulation, where they would “activate” and begin radicalizing agents around them, only to disappear again after the disaster period was over. The spectrum of types alone proved too difficult to implement, as various issues such as displaying the types prevented it from being a reasonable goal. It was decided to greatly simplify the model to what it is now so that it could reach a point of being completely functional within the timeframe.

Much of the development of the model itself was difficult to complete, as we were relatively inexperienced in working with Python, and incredibly inexperienced when it came to working with a model such as the Schelling Segregation model. We had plenty of technical issues when getting the model to run, and additional issues when trying to collaborate through Git due to unexplained bugs during the sharing process on GitHub. For the development of the model itself, the most difficult aspect of implementation was fixing bugs relating to the spread of agents. Adding the additional types to agents led to a lot of unexpected issues where agents would inexplicably bunch up or start the simulation in a very organized manner. This led to the agents erratically struggling to break from those starting clumps throughout the simulation. Additionally, implementing an algorithm to count the formation of clusters or echo-chamber was found to be difficult, since the team was quite unfamiliar with the most suitable techniques for this case. To address this, we explored various methods and determined that the flood-fill algorithm was the most effective for this scenario. Its ability to effectively identify groups of the same objects/agents for grid-based environments made it well-suited for identifying groups of disinformed agents in our model. 

We plan to add a specific disaster system to the final simulation so that we can explore the volatile effects of specific phenomena of information and disinformation. We aim to observe this by introducing occasional disasters, during which human agents move regardless of their happiness due to a sense of panic, and providing bot agents with a significantly higher chance of influencing and misinforming them. We could also experiment with the possibility of bot agents and human agents being removed and replaced, due to either bots being detected by the platform or human agents leaving a platform due to the disinformation. Alongside these changes, we’d add more tracking about how the platform becomes radicalized specifically around the times of disasters.
